article.description: Travis Diener and Terry Sanders scored 13 points each, and Marquette stayed undefeated by beating Grambling 71-55 Friday night.
article.headline: Marquette moves to 6-0 on season
article.story: MILWAUKEE (AP) -- To say it was a satisfying week for No. 24 Marquette would be an understatement. The Golden Eagles, not letting down following their emotional victory over Notre Dame on Monday, stayed undefeated with an efficient 71-55 triumph over Grambling State on Friday night. Travis Diener and Terry Sanders scored 13 points each, Scott Merritt had 12 and Karon Bradley 10 for Marquette (6-0). "It wasn't an easy week, with a lot of (term) papers due and getting ready for finals," Marquette coach Tom Crean said. "We didn't always play efficient, but we played hard." Grambling (1-4) was led by Brion Rush's 24 points. Paul Haynes added 13 and Larry Haygood 11. Diener hit a 3-pointer to start the second half, putting Marquette ahead by 21. The Tigers responded with nine straight points to close to 45-33. But Grambling managed only eight points in the final 10 minutes, five coming in the final minute. The Golden Eagles, who hit their first five shots, used runs of 10-1 and 10-0 in building a 42-28 lead at halftime. Marquette broke the Grambling press for easy baskets and held the Tigers to 31 percent shooting (8-for-26) in the first half. "It was something we knew we had to do," Crean said, "because that's something that they do well. They're very athletic." Five of Grambling's first six field goals were 3-pointers. The Tigers finished with 11 3-pointers, six by Rush, but shot only 37 percent (18-for-49). Marquette, which had eight 3-pointers, shot 49 percent (25-for-51). Sanders established a career high with his 13 points on 5-of-6 from the field in only 21 minutes. He had only four points and sat out much of the Notre Dame game after getting into early foul trouble. He said his teammates told him to forget his last game. "The guys just told me to go out and be aggressive and good things will happen. I guess they did," Sanders said. " "We were really happy with the way he stepped up," Crean said. "This will do wonders for his confidence." The Golden Eagles are idle until traveling to Arizona on Dec. 13. "I like that we're 6-0, but it'll be a whole new element going into that game," Crean said. "But let's go see where we're at. We're anxious to see how we come out of it."
